44698450.property_description: Set along a quiet side road lined with pretty cottages, and being only moments from the village's bowling green and cricket pitch, this delightful two bedroom cottage offers a wealth of charm and character. Set behind a picket fence, the entrance porch and multi pane sealed unit cottage style windows adorn the front elevation and give a sense of what lies within. The sitting room with its exposed ceiling beams and large cast iron wood burning stove make for a cosy retreat. A formal dining room with alcove storage and panelled walls is too a welcoming space. However, the rear of the property has been thoughtfully extended in order to create a bright kitchen breakfast/garden room, with the addition of an orangery style timber framed glazed space. The double height ceilings add an abundance of natural light, and from this room, direct access is gained onto the rear garden. Other internal rooms of note are the fitted bathroom and two good sized double bedrooms.The rear garden is large, laid generously with lawn and enclosed. Side access for vehicles through a five bar gate allows for parking behind the property. The popular village pub and store are a short distance away, making this a great home.   The village of Bircham lies on the border of the Sandringham Estate, about 7 miles from the north Norfolk coast and comprises of three parishes:- Great Bircham, Bircham Tofts and Bircham Newton. Great Bircham has a good farm shop with deli, a church, St Mary's and the Kings Head Hotel with award winning restaurant. There is also a fully restored windmill, considered to be the only working windmill in this part of the county, where visitors can climb five floors up to the fan stage and on windy days, can see the sails and milling machinery turning and admire the view. The mill also has a bakery, tea room, gift shop, small children's farm and cycle hire centre. Bircham Newton has a small, private trout fishing lake and the Church of All Saints, one of the smallest in the county, with no porch, few windows and Victorian box pews. Nelson's daughter Horatia married Philip Ward, who was the rector and brought up a large family at Church Farm. Bircham Tofts is recorded in the Domesday book as Stoftstan, referring to its stony soil and merged with Bircham Newton in 1719.
